\begin_layout Standard
At equilibrium, the projection of the orbit on the poloidal cross section
 is a closed curve.
 For either mirror-trapped or passing orbit, we define the bounce time [F.
 Porcelli, R.
 Stankiewicz, and W.
 Kerner, Phys.
 Plasmas 1 1994]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{b}=\oint d\tau=\oint\frac{d\psi}{\dot{\psi}}=\oint\frac{d\theta}{\dot{\theta}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as the time it takes to close an equilibrium orbit on the poloidal plane.
 We assume that perturbations have the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X^{\left(1\right)}=\hat{X}^{\left(1\right)}\left(r,\theta\right)\exp\left(-i\omega t+in\phi\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{X}^{\left(1\right)}\left(r,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 is complex, and we take the real part of RHS for any physical variable,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\left(1\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\color blue
for internal kink mode, the displacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\xi}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\xi}=\xi_{\theta}^{\prime}\mathbf{e}_{\theta}+\xi_{r}^{\prime}\mathbf{e}_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{r}^{\prime}=\xi_{0}\exp\left(i\left(\phi-\theta-\omega t\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 within the region 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

 rational surface 
\begin_inset Formula $r=r_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 With cylindrical approximation, it can apply the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\vec{\xi}=0$
\end_inset

, and thus obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\theta}^{\prime}=-i\xi_{0}\exp\left[i\left(\phi-\theta-\omega t\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the covariant forms of the perturbation are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{r}=\xi_{0}\exp\left(i\left(\phi-\theta-\omega t\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{\theta}=-i\xi_{0}r\exp\left(i\left(\phi-\theta-\omega t\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color blue
within the region 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

 surface.
 Similarly, the covariant forms of the perturbation are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{r}=\xi_{0}\left(\frac{\Delta r-r+\left(r_{s}-\Delta r/2\right)}{\Delta r}\right)\exp\left(i\left(\phi-\theta-\omega t\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{\theta}=-i\xi_{0}r\left(\frac{\Delta r-2r+\left(r_{s}-\Delta r/2\right)}{\Delta r}\right)\exp\left(i\left(\phi-\theta-\omega t\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color blue
in the inertial region 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}-\frac{\Delta r}{2}\leq r\leq r_{s}+\frac{\Delta r}{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 And 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{r}=\xi_{\theta}=0$
\end_inset

 in the rest region.
\end_layout

